            <h2>Negated Verbs</h2>
            <p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">M</span>odern English has many dialects and non standard forms.
            In standard English, double negatives cancel each other out. So if we say '<em>He can't not eat it</em>' the two
            negatives cancel each other out, and we get a positive: he eats it. In Old English, double, or multiple, negation
            doesn't cancel out the negation, but actually reinforces it. Multiple negation seems to have been used for emphasis:
            the more negations included in a sentence, the more the negative is stressed. So we might see a sentence like the one 
            below from the Gospel of John: '<em>Ne geseah næfre nan mann god' - literally '<em>has not seen never no man God</em>
            or to give the modern translation of this line of the gospel 'no one has ever seen God'. Here the negations in the Old
            English sentence are used to emphasise this point, and they do not cancel each other out.
       
        </p>
           
